Xunlei Li Deputy CEO and Chief Economist Haitong Securities Co., Ltd.    Mr. Xunlei Li is the Chief Economist and Deputy General Manager at Haitong Securities Co., Ltd. He serves as a member of the Shanghai Municipal People's Congress Standing Committee, the NPC Financial and Economic Committee, and a Central Committee member of the 93 Society. He is also a contributing member at the Chinese Finance 40 Forum and a member of the New Academic Committee at the Shanghai Institute of Finance.   Mr. Li obtained a Master's degree and a Bachelor's degree in Economics from the Shanghai University of Finance and Economics in 1991 and 1985 respectively, and had engaged in macroeconomics research, international finance and equity research at the Shanghai University of Finance and former Junan Securities Research Institute. In 1999, Mr. Li was Director of the Research Institute, General Manager of Sales and Trading department, Assistant to President, and Chief Economist at Guotai Junan Securities Co., Ltd. In October 2011, he joined Haitong Securities Co., Ltd.  Mr. Li has more than 20 years of experience in the area of macroeconomics and capital market research, and has written and translated numerous economic and securities literature. He has also published articles and research reports in various academic journals, and has received numerous awards for his contribution.   As a veteran in the research of onshore securities market, Mr. Li has successfully led the Guotai Junan research team to rank top 3 for the New Fortune Magazine "Best Local Research Team" award for six consecutive years. In both 2013 and 2014, under Mr. Li’s leadership, the Haitong Securities Research Team was awarded top place for the New Fortune Magazine Best Local Research Team and Most Influential Local Research Team. Mr. Li has also received several honours from the media for his personal contribution including "Local Outstanding Research Leader", "Shanghai Top Ten Youth Economic Figures", "Shanghai Top Ten Financial Innovator", and "Best Chief Economist".



 
 




 
About Eastmoney.com

East Money Information Co., Ltd. (300059.SZ) is an operator of financial and economic information service platform. The Company is involved in the collection, integration and analysis of original information from data suppliers, as well as the provision of stock quotation, financial and economic information and data analysis services to terminal users through its financial data terminal platforms. The Company primarily offers paid financial data services, financial e-commerce services and Internet advertisement services through its Website Eastmoney (www.eastmoney.com). The Eastmoney Website provides financial information through several channels, including finance, stock, fund, financing, futures, bond, bank and insurance, among others.

About Qingyanliu Village (????) – one of the best known Taobao village in China

Yiwu in eastern China's Zhejiang Province has not only won world fame as an international distribution hub for small commodities, but has also brought business opportunities to local farmers through development of e-commerce.  Yiwu is the only county-level city that has been granted recognition as a model city in the national level

Yiwu's Qingyanliu Village is home to around 700 households.  Yet, praised as "China's No. 1 e-commerce village - ???????", more than 2,800 online stores have sprung up with annual turnover of up to 20 billion yuan, as of end of 2014.  Every year, more than 4 million packages are shipped from Qingyanliu to domestic and international destinations.  The online shops at the Village, which are engaged in selling more than 30 million of such daily-used merchandise as scarves, toys and lamps per day, have also attracted some 30 express delivery companies and more than 8,000 workers and business people from other parts of the country.

Qingyanliu is a showcase of e-commerce development in China's rural areas. In the past eight or nine years, Qingyanliu village has become the gathering place for students to start their own businesses, as well as an incubator for entrepreneurship and innovation.  More than 8,000 college students have engaged in e-commerce business in Qingyanliu village. Furthermore, business people from other areas of Zhejiang, and even from Chongqing Municipality in southwest China, Anhui in the eastern part of the country and Liaoning in the northeast, have flocked to Qingyanliu. Any of them may rent a house in the village and start an online business with a computer. All parts of the business process, from online shop registration to goods purchases and delivery, can be done inside the village.

What Is a Taobao Village?

According to Alibaba, a Taobao village is any place where 10 percent of local population is engaged in online retailing and makes at least 10 million yuan ($1.6 million) from the Taobao platform annually. Alibaba's statistics show that there were already 20 such villages across China in 2013 and 212 villages in 2014 spreading in 10 municipalities and provinces. These Taobao villages include over 70,000 online stores offering more than 280,000 jobs.  Alibaba estimates that in three to five years, there will be at least 100,000 Taobao villages in China. By then, over 1 billion yuan ($160 million) of transaction volume will take place on Taobao's e-commerce platform every day.

 









